  "prompt": "Why does the sun rise in the east and set in the west but not the north and south?",
  "response": "The sun rises in the east and sets in the west due to the rotation of the Earth on its axis. The Earth rotates from west to east, which means that as it spins, different parts of the Earth's surface move into the sunlight, creating the appearance that the sun is rising in the east and setting in the west.\n\nThe direction of sunrise and sunset is influenced by the Earth's axial tilt and orbit around the sun, which can cause variations in the exact position of sunrise and sunset throughout the year. However, the general pattern of the sun rising in the east and setting in the west remains consistent.\n\nThe reason the sun does not rise in the north or south is that the Earth's rotation is around a tilted axis that runs from the North Pole to the South Pole. As a result, the sun's apparent path in the sky is predominantly east to west, rather than north to south, in most locations on Earth.",
